THE FOURTH WARD
----------------------------------------------------------------------
    
    Some people, local estate agents mainly, insist on calling St
    Margarets 'the village' even though most of us know that our slice
    of paradise is really a 'dormitory' or 'a railway town' which
    didn't really come into existence until the railway station was
    opened on Monday 2nd October 1876. Before then it was about 2,000
    acres of pasture, arable land, wood and common. We should be
    grateful that we live in 'St Margarets'. The local businessmen who
    helped pay for the new station wanted to call the neighbourhood
    'Ailsa Bridge'. Phew!

